        "answer":  "Position: No — in the modern economy, career mobility is more beneficial than long-term loyalty to a single employer. Reason: The implicit social contract of lifelong employment in exchange for loyalty has largely dissolved. Most companies no longer offer this — mass layoffs, restructuring, and outsourcing have made long-term job security rare. Meanwhile, research shows that workers who change jobs every few years earn significantly higher lifetime incomes than those who stay. Example: A LinkedIn analysis of over 20 million career histories found that the most successful professionals changed companies multiple times — gaining skills, perspective, and salary increments that internal promotions rarely match. The skill set built through diverse experiences is also more resilient than deep expertise in one organizational context. Wrap-up: Loyalty to craft, values, and professional relationships matters enormously. Loyalty to a single employer, in an era when employers rarely reciprocate, is strategically unwise.",
