        "question":  "Do you agree that following your passion is always good career advice?",
        "answer":  "Position: I believe \u0027follow your passion\u0027 is well-intentioned but potentially misleading career advice. Reason: Passions can be vague, changeable, and not all passions translate into viable careers. Cal Newport\u0027s research argues that passion often follows mastery — you develop deep passion for work as you become exceptionally good at it, not before. Starting with skills, then finding work where you can apply and develop them, is often more effective than chasing a pre-existing passion. Example: People who said they were passionate about art, music, or acting often discover the commercial reality of those industries produces more frustration than fulfillment. Meanwhile, people who developed deep competency in areas like software engineering or medicine often report high passion for work they initially chose pragmatically. Wrap-up: Rather than following passion, I would advise developing mastery and pursuing work that is challenging, meaningful, and well-remunerated. Passion often follows from that process.",
