        "question":  "Do you agree that modern life is too fast-paced?",
        "answer":  "Position: Yes — the pace of modern life has outstripped the pace at which humans evolved to process it. Reason: Human attention systems, social cognition, and stress response evolved for environments with limited information, predictable rhythms, and clear social structures. Modern life bombards us with decisions, notifications, and information at volumes our nervous systems were not designed to handle sustainably. Example: The average office worker in 2024 receives over 120 emails per day and is interrupted every 11 minutes. Research by Gloria Mark at the University of California found that after an interruption, it takes an average of 23 minutes to fully regain concentration. The cumulative cost to deep work and wellbeing is enormous. Wrap-up: The solution is not to reject modernity but to design better buffers — deliberate spaces for slow thinking, deep work, human connection, and unstructured rest within modern life\u0027s framework.",
