        "answer":  "Position: I strongly prefer a small number of deep, trusting friendships over a large network of casual connections. Reason: Deep friendships provide the emotional safety, honest feedback, and genuine support that actually improve quality of life during difficulty. Casual acquaintances provide pleasant interaction and social variety but generally do not mobilize meaningfully when things go wrong. Research on social support and wellbeing shows that depth, not breadth, of social connection is what most powerfully predicts resilience and life satisfaction. Example: Robin Dunbar\u0027s research on social cognition suggests that humans can maintain no more than five deeply intimate relationships at any given time — and that these five relationships account for disproportionate amounts of emotional wellbeing. Stretching energy across 500 connections dilutes each bond below the threshold of genuine intimacy. Wrap-up: In an era of performative social media presence, the most counter-cultural and ultimately healthiest investment is going deeper rather than wider in friendship.",
