        "question":  "Do you agree that humor is an essential part of a healthy life?",
        "answer":  "Position: Yes — humor is not trivial. It is one of the most sophisticated, health-promoting, and socially essential human capacities. Reason: Humor releases endorphins, reduces cortisol, builds social bonds, and provides cognitive flexibility — the ability to hold incongruent frames simultaneously. Psychologically, the capacity to laugh at oneself is a marker of emotional maturity and resilience. Even in tragedy, the right humor can be a profoundly humanizing force. Example: The work of Norman Cousins, who used comedy films as part of his recovery from a serious illness, was among the first documented cases that laughter had measurable physiological benefits. Subsequent research confirmed that laughter improves immune function, pain tolerance, and cardiovascular health. Wrap-up: A life without humor is not just joyless — it is cognitively rigid, socially impoverished, and physiologically less healthy. Humor deserves to be taken more seriously.",
